<UserControl x:Class="ActiproSoftware.ProductSamples.SyntaxEditorSamples.QuickStart.GoToLine.MainControl"
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
	xmlns:shared="http://schemas.actiprosoftware.com/winfx/xaml/shared" 
	xmlns:editor="http://schemas.actiprosoftware.com/winfx/xaml/syntaxeditor" 
    >
    
	<DockPanel>
		<shared:PixelSnapper DockPanel.Dock="Top" Margin="20,10">
			<StackPanel Orientation="Horizontal">
				<TextBlock Text="Line number " VerticalAlignment="Center" />
				<TextBox x:Name="lineNumberTextBox" Width="50" Text="50" VerticalAlignment="Center" />
				<Button Margin="3,0,0,0" Content="Go to Line" VerticalAlignment="Center" Click="OnGoToLineButtonClick" />
			</StackPanel>
		</shared:PixelSnapper>

		<editor:SyntaxEditor x:Name="editor" IsLineNumberMarginVisible="True">
				<editor:EditorDocument x:Name="document" xml:space="preserve"><![CDATA[This QuickStart shows how easy it is to implement go to line
functionality, which is just a matter of setting the caret's position:
editor.Caret.Position = new TextPosition(lineIndex, 0);

The caret moves to the specified line index and ensures that it is
scrolled into view.  To test this feature, enter a line number in
the TextBox above and click the "Go to Line" button.

We've added a number of nonsense lines below to give the document
some length so that the scroll to caret feature can be demoed.

In addition, this line ensures the caret scrolls to the view's middle:
editor.ActiveView.Scroller.ScrollLineToVisibleMiddle();

